Yesterday we received guidance from the Governor's office and the MHSAA in regards to Fall sports. We are excited to share details with everyone - but want to do so when we have the facts straight. PLEASE show patience as we navigate all the guidance, changes, and protocols for safety and care.
Meetings to gain clarity are taking place in the West Michigan Conference and across the state this afternoon, tomorrow, and throughout the weekend. As we gain a clear picture of details we will pass those along to our student-athletes, parents, and faithful fans! In the meantime, have a great weekend and remember - GO NORSE!

-Jeff Cooke

post_text: Something to think about considering the times we are in.
shared_text:
Thomas Guskey‚ÄéStandards Based Learning and Grading
April 24 at 7:44 PM ¬∑

If there was ever a time to abandon percentage grades, it is now. Universities have gone to satisfactory/incomplete grades, recognizing the impossible task of faculty distinguishing 5 categories of student performance. Can we expect HS teachers, where there is even greater inequity among students, to accurately distinguish 100 categories?

post_text:
Hello Norse Nation:

It is very likely that you woke up this morning to the news that Governor Whitmer has declared a State of Emergency in Michigan with 2 confirmed cases of COVID-19. Please be assured that we continue to have constant communication with our Health Department who have a direct line to the Michigan Department of Health and the CDC.

We will continue to make decisions based upon facts and recommendations from our local, State, and National health experts. Attached, please find a few of the resources shared with us. Please be sure to continue to reach out with questions as we navigate this unprecedented time. As always, we will attempt to use facts as we make decisions on our students, staff, and community‚Äôs safety/health/wellbeing.

Thank you!

We will continue to make decisions based upon facts and recommendations from our local, State, and National health experts. Attached, please find a few of the resources shared with us. Please be sure to continue to reach out with questions as we navigate this unprecedented time. February 19, 2019 at 2:37 PM ¬∑

Now that MHSAA Staff have completed their visits to all three Battle of The Fans Contest Finalists, it‚Äôs time to engage communities in a final show of support.

Fans can cast votes for their favorite 2019 BOTF Finalist in one (or all) of the four following ways:
‚Ä¢ Like the corresponding photo via the MHSAA Facebook Page.
‚Ä¢ Share the photo on your own Facebook Timeline.
‚Ä¢ Like the corresponding photo via the MHSAA Instagram account.
‚Ä¢ Like & Retweet the corresponding tweet (with the hashtag #BOTFVote) from the MHSAA Twitter account.

Likes, shares, and RTs will be tallied for each Finalist when the vote concludes at 4:00 PM on Thursday, February 21. The MHSAA Student Advisory Council will consider social media activity when selecting the eventual Battle of The Fans Champion for 2019.

Best of luck to all three of our Finalists!
For full contest details, visit https://www.mhsaa.com/BOTF

post_text:
Athletic Tickets in the HS Office this week M-Thurs. 7-11am!

Also, season sports passes for entry to all home games will be sold next week in the high school lobby the following dates and times:

August 6 9-11 am
August 7 6-7:30 pm
August 8 9-11 am

Passes can also be purchased at Fast Track on August 21 from 10 am till 6 pm and at the first home football contest on August 24.

Cost for passes are:
Family pass $200
Adult Pass $50
Student Pass $40

Parents wishing to sell tickets to offset the cost of a pass will have the opportunity to sign up for events at those times. 5 events worked (signed up to work) would cover a family pass for the year.

A schedule of all events will be available at the above times.

Any additional question please contact Al Karaba @ akaraba@nmps.net

Please spread the word!

post_text:
North Muskegon Schools would like to remind everyone that when we make posts to keep replies & comments positive, or to yourself.

We are a #BeNice School and are extremely proud of what our students' have achieved. If you see art, academics, performances, or athletics that are not of interest to you - we ask that you keep it to yourself. In an Age of Social Media it is up to both Staff & Parents to show proper etiquette when using these platforms. Down talking and cyberbullying is easy from behind a screen - and if we find such behavior, your post will be removed and your account banned from participating on NMPS's Page.

#BeNice #GoNorse

The dates for the 2018 spring and summer Mercy Health Student Heart Screenings are now open. The dates are March 21, July 18, August 8, and August 22. The cardiologists recommend screening students every year so if you're interested please sign up.

Students must be in 9th, 10th 11th or 12th grade this year or entering 9th grade in the fall of 2018.

The link to information and online registration can be found here: http://www.mercyhealthmuskegon.com/studentheart
